engineer_note: The 38th, Red River, Dean Keeton, and IH 35 Service Road corridors were timed as a group, for an average travel time reduction of 9.1% across all four corridors.

The Burnet corridor has seen tremendous growth in the past several years, especially in the Domain area (Braker to Gracy Farms).  As part of the retiming, the times of day that the side street protected left-turns were extended at Esperanza and Palm, reducing green time on Burnet Road.  In addition, the standards by which we calculate pedestrian crossing times has been recently updated, which required longer crossing times crossing Burnet, reducing green time on Burnet Road when pedestrians are present. Finally, some phasing changes were made, which allowed more vehicular traffic to enter the corridor - so despite the minimal delay increase, throughput has increased.
Adjustments made to Ben White/Lamar/360 to reduce queuing for WB Ben White.  Traffic Responsive operations fine-tuned.
Retimed for system improvements; data not used in comprehensive analysis

Cycle lengths decreased to synchronize corridor with Cameron and Manor corridors.  Lower cycle lengths allowed quicker service to vehicles & pedestrians from growing Mueller area. Green time adjusted at Manor to clear backups in peak periods.
Retimed for system improvements; data not used in comprehensive analysis

Adjusted cycle lengths from Comal to Springdale to synchronize better with Airport corridor.  Intersections east of Springdale needed ongoing monitoring, to match the changing traffic patterns at US 183 overpass construction. Leading pedestrian Interval implemented at Cedar.
Cycle lengths increased at intersections surrounding Parmer, to synchronize up with changes along Parmer corridor.  Resulting cycles were expected to slightly increase delays along Metric.
Cycle length increased for all timing plans during daylight hours.  Resulted in longer green times and improved progression for vehicles traveling along Parmer.
Cycle lengths changed for AM/PM peak plans, reducing side street delay.  Green times adjusted to improve progression for off peak and overnight plans.
Coordinated only between William Cannon and Slaughter.

Major signal construction project implemented at North Plaza, resulting in timing adjustments being made for improved traffic flow to I-35.  Timing adjustments made to intersections from Parkfield to Lamar.
Retimed for system improvements; Before = After, data not used in comprehensive analysis
Cycle lengths reduced for intersections near US 290 to reduce delay for all vehicular demand at US 290 intersection, as well as new phasing sequence designed to improve safety.
Retimed mid December.  Good data collection dates will be October or November for before and January 2018 for after.
Retimed for system improvements; data not used in comprehensive analysis

Increased cycle lengths resulted in improved coordination across William Cannon and Slaughter corridors, with a tradeoff of slightly increased delays for lower volume intersections further down the corridor.  Weekend plans adjusted to accommodate higher volumes in Sunset Valley area.

Cycle length was reduced for AM/PM peak plans, reducing side street delay. Implemented leading pedestrian intervals at several intersections along corridor.  Those two actions contributed to expected increase in delay along corridor.

Slightly increased cycle length and adjusted splits to accommodate traffic conditions. Added FYA to about 5 locations; Oak Springs previously only had a permissive WBLT but with the FYA installation, it now runs a protected/permissive operation. Implemented advanced walk at Highland Mall. Due to the US 183 construction, signal at Levander loop was bagged and taken out of operation (temporary).

Cycle lengths were matched for all three signals, which resulted in higher traffic volumes getting through each intersection, but limited coordination possible with higher cycle lengths and variable intersection spacing.

At Great Hills and Braker, coordination was adjusted to work with the cross street instead of NB and SB 183.  At Balcones Woods, Duval, and Oak Knoll, signals were set to run free except for the AM and PM peaks when progression is provided in the peak direction of 183.

Cycle length were further optimized by time of day and changing traffic volumes.  Some peak periods saw increases in delay for the side streets, while traffic along 360 should experience longer green times and better progression.

Corridor was modified to change according to demand-based setting during non-peak periods, for lower traffic volumes, and quicker service to side street and pedestrian volumes.  As a result, no coordination for traffic flow.  Corridor remained in coordination with nearby US 183 intersections during peak periods, with limited vehicular flow along Jollyville.

Cycle lengths were adjusted by time of day to reflect traffic volumes from the shopping generators in the immediate area.  Signals west of Jollyville had cycles reduced by half, which will result in more red time for traffic along Great Hills, but reduces delay and queuing for all side street traffic, which will improve safety in the adjacent parking lots.
Brought into coordination for AM and PM peaks.  7-9 AM and 430-630 PM.
Cycle lengths increase to accommodate larger traffic volumes along corridor.
These signals were re-timed over the course of the year.
No changes made, with volumes not apparently changed from US 183 construction.
Coordinated timing plans were developed for weekdays to allow for progression through the corridor.  Flashing yellow arrows were installed at all intersections in the corridor to improve safety.

Cycle lengths were increased at bottleneck intersections during peak hours to increase throughput.  Additionally, a traffic responsive system was installed for US 290 westbound approaching William Cannon, that can increase green time whenever vehicular queues back up beyond a certain threshold.

Cycle lengths were adjusted lower during the AM peak period, except for Lakeline and Lake Creek, where increases were required based on traffic demand. Northbound 183 progression was prioritized from Lakeline Mall through Lakeline.  Southbound progression was prioritized from Lakeline Mall to Lake Creek.

Cycle lengths were reduced to coordinate with Riverside.  New left turn phases were activated at Elmont. The heavily used PHB north of Riverside was placed into coordination in the system, to improve safety and operations.

No changes to cycle lengths or green times, and settings for synchronization were optimized.  Several left turns at Jollyville and at Metric were converted to “protected only” at certain times of day to increase safety.
